@endnode

@node Purpose

Why did I wrote ShadowStart?

Well, I was sitting in front of my Amiga and trying to start a program,
but I didn't get it to run correctly...  (ya know this... ;-)
So I tried to start the program after booting without startup-sequence,
but this program could only be run from the Workbench...   *damn* ;)
But how to load the Workbench without executing any programs in the
WBStartup-drawer?

This was the point I got the idea to write a program that pops up a little
requester at startup, which lets you select if you want to disable 
the "WBStartup" drawer and/or the "User-Startup" file!
ShadowStart was born...  :-)

As it should be possible to select this on every startup, ShadowStart
checks if you pressed the @{"activation-key" Link activation} (ie. hold it down during startup) and
then pops up a nice requester asking you what should be disabled.

@{b}New for version 1.3@{ub} is the automatic validation check. Program execution
is delayed until the SYS: partion is validated (See @{"Usage section" Link usage} for details).


If you think that ShadowStart would be usefull for you, then look into 
the @{" Installation " Link Installation} part of this documentation on how you can do this...


@endnode

@node Requirements

@{u}ShadowStart needs:@{uu}

   · any Amiga :-)

   · V40 version of ShadowStart needs:
       Kickstart/Workbench 3.1
       (the 3.1 lowlevel.library must be available)
   
   · V37 version of ShadowStart needs:
       Kickstart/Workbench 2.04 or higher

   · and a correct @{" installation " Link Installation}  ,-)


@endnode

@node Installation

@{u}Installation is very easy:@{uu}

 1) Depending on what Kickstart you use, copy either the 2.0+ or the 3.1 
    version of "ShadowStart" in any directory you want.
    I recommend the "c:" directory.

 2) Load your "s:Startup-Sequence" into a text-editor and add the following
    line @{b}after@{ub} the SetPatch-command:
    "<path>ShadowStart"
    (If it's in your "c:" directory, you must enter "c:ShadowStart".)

 3) This documentation may copied to the directory,
    where you store your guide files.


@endnode

@node Usage

If ShadowStart is @{" installed " Link Installation} correctly the usage is
as follows...

If you want to disable the "WBStartup" drawer or the "User-Startup" file
during startup, then simply hold down the version dependant @{"activation-key" Link activation}
after a reset or after you switched the computer on...
If ShadowStart notices that the @{"activation-key" Link activation} is down, it will pop a 
requester, asking you what you want to disable.
You can select one of the following buttons:

    @{" WB + User " Link shadow}     (disables both, WBStartup and User-Startup)
    @{" WB        " Link shadow}     (disables only WBStartup)
    @{" User      " Link shadow}     (disables only User-Startup)
    @{" NewShell  " Link shadow}     (opens a shell window)
    @{" Cancel    " Link shadow}     (you guess what it does...  ;-)


But what does it mean, when ShadowStart "disables" them?
Well, it's just simple... ShadowStart renames the WBStartup-drawer and/or
the User-Startup file to prevent them from being executed! :)
("WBStartup"/"WBStartup.info" is renamed to "_WBStartup"/"_WBstartup.info"
and "User-Startup" is renamed to "_User-Startup")

After startup the drawer and the file stay renamed!
If you want the original names back, you can either rename them by hand
or run ShadowStart again.
But normally there is no need to do this...

If you boot without holding down the @{"activation-key" Link activation} the WBStartup-drawer and
the User-Startup file are automatically renamed to their original name!

New for version 1.2:
With the NewShell-button you can open a shell-window.
The execution of the startup-sequence is paused until you send a 
`break' to ShadowStart.
If ShadowStart was executed directly after SetPatch, it has normaly
the process number 1.
Typing "break 1" in the shell-window will stop ShadowStart and the
execution of the startup-sequence is continued.
Don't forget to close the shell-window, so that the Workbench can 
reset the screen (if needed).


@{b}New for version 1.3:@{ub}
Before any key checks are performed ShadowStart checks if the SYS: partition
is currently being validated.
If yes, Shadowstart waits 3 seconds and checks the disk state again.
When the validation is finished, ShadowStart automatically continues with its
normal execution.
The main effect of this feature is that startup execution will be delayed
until the SYS: partition is validated (no more disk-trashing on startup).
The validation check is always performed, if the @{"activation-key" Link activation} is
pressed or not.



@{u}Restrictions:@{uu} If you press the @{"activation-key" Link activation} to early when starting up,
              ShadowStart maybe don't recognize that it was pressed!
              But this may only happens after a cold-reset
              (ie. turning on the computer).


@endnode

@node activation


Since version 1.2 I included an additional ShadowStart version for
Kickstart/Workbench 2.0+, but due to key checking under 2.0 I had to
change the previous used spacebar as activation-key to something different.

If you use the @{b}2.0+ (V37)@{ub} version of ShadowStart, you should use either the 
@{b}left or the right ALT@{ub} key to activate ShadowStart.

If you use the @{b}3.1 (V40)@{ub} version of ShadowStart, you should use the @{b}spacebar@{ub}
to activate ShadowStart.


@endnode

